Beatles\x18\xb2\x01""\xcc\x01\n\x02US\x12\x12\n\x10\xccd\x8d\x1f\xbe\xd4JF\x99\xe6r\xc6\xff\xf0}\x0e\x12\x12\n\x10W#\x0e+\x01\xdbO\x9f\x88\xc4T\x11b$3?\x12\x12\n\x10\xef\xf4\xc3}\xbesMk\x86\x01\x96\xa8\x10\xecc\x00\x12\x12\n\x10v\xa1\x0f\xed\xb8zA\xc6\xb1\x03e\xcd""\xacF\x06\x12\x12\n\x10\x05\x97\xd8\xa2\xed\x11C\n\x93\xc4\xec\xfc\xc3\xf32\x81\x12\x12\n\x10\x90\xc6\xa7L\x06\x8cB\xe0\xa0c\x0c\xbb\x9e-o\xf6\x12\x12\n\x10\xae~\xeaRo\nIw\x96\xa7\xa0YSO\xd5\xd3\x12\x12\n\x10\xc4\xed\xf2\x9cQtD\x8d\x8d\xf5\x0b\xb4\xdbT\x19\x95\x12\x12\n\x10{\x13\xfbc\x8avDS\xbc\xdejAn\xa5p\x1a\x12\x12\n\x10\xfb\x00\x17\xebh\xd5Kf\x85\x07V\x07CS\xc3A*\x14\n\x12\n\x10\xaeKB\xb3\x8dVF\xce\x993\xd8\\\xb6O\x08\xf8*\x14\n\x12\n\x10@\x03\x1a\xab5{@E\xa0\xef\xa8\x1cPE\xdb-*\x14\n\x12\n\x10\x0cE\xf9e#\x16Im\xba\xa3.jf\xcc\xa9R*\x14\n\x12\n\x10\x9cQ\xd3i) Ax\xac\x7fv\x1d2\xab\xa8\x10*\x14\n\x12\n\x10\x9e\x1f\x1f\xac\xfbSO\xb1\x88oC\x8bx\x8d\xc0\xe9*\x14\n\x12\n\x10\xf6\xc6L\x85\xca*K_\xaa:\x90r\xa8&\xb8\xdd*\x14\n\x12\n\x10\x1f\xba~\xb2""\x01L\xc9\xbc\xc8R\xfbd\xf3\xbb\xdc*\x14\n\x12\n\x10W\x1f\x11h\x92\x8aBU\xb3\xbdj\xe2\x879\xbc(*\x14\n\x12\n\x10\n\x8b\x87\xc8\xe87D\xc6\x8fr\xc3Y\xc4\xa9\x08\x05*\x14\n\x12\n\x10\x15\xac}\x16@\xceK\xa3\xb3O\x00\t\xbd\xd9\n\xeb*\x14\n\x12\n\x10)\xbc\xd6\xec\xdeWCc\xb8\xd9y\xad\x1d\xda\x96\xde*\x14\n\x12\n\x10+\xa3\xf1\xd9\xb0\xe6O\x8f\xb1\x16:\x01\xe8Sh\xb5*\x14\n\x12\n\x10U\x93CH|HN\xda\x94\\z,\xdcW\xf6\x07*\x14\n\x12\n\x10\xcb\x08\xfd\xe6\xd8\xacO\xcc\xa2Jz\x12]\xc4\xbe.*\x14\n\x12\n\x10\xe0\xca\xb7\xb2\xa7\xb8L\xb2\x8d\x995|\x95\xb5\xd2x*\x14\n\x12\n\x10-L\xe8\xecd""ED\x9e(\xf7:\xc82O\xbe*\x14\n\x12\n\x10~\r\xf0\x06:\x0cFg\xa8I>\xed\x1c\xbee\xdd*\x14\n\x12\n\x10\xa4}\x8c\xd1\x8a\xe4J\x9d\x88px\x9f\xf5,\x16\xd8*\x14\n\x12\n\x10\x1b\x7f\x8e\x82\xa3QN\xe8\xa9\x81\xa5?\x11\xb7\xd8m*\x14\n\x12\n\x101\x99\x92S\x18\xb8@\x9f\x9d\x9f\xf2\x170\xd1\x1c,*\x14\n\x12\n\x10\xd6m\xaa\x80\x1c\rOs\x9er\xc54\x16\x0f\xdd\xaf*\x14\n\x12\n\x10&\xab\xc9\x0c\xbf\x9bK?\x8b9\xbdw\xfa^5\x91*\x14\n\x12\n\x10{@\x9fj\x16KG\x11\x82\xd4""\xa7\x11;\x94\xd32\x14\n\x12\n\x10\xf5\xcf\x7fU\x11OI\xba\x98\x10\xc4\xfa\x99\xbe\x89\x0c2\x14\n\x12\n\x10n\x87\xda\xaf\xcfmJ\x05\xab\x0f\xdfV\xb5Y>\xfb2\x14\n\x12\n\x10El5\x02\xcf\xbeO\x8d\x98bM$\xfaf\xf5\xa2:\x14\n\x12\n\x10@\xc6F\xf7\x06`AP\xb0D\x89\xc0\xc76#\x01:\x14\n\x12\n\x10\x8e\x8f\x9e\xe6\tdG\xae\xab\xb2t\x01m:\x84\x1a:\x14\n\x12\n\x10{\x9b\x8d\x7f\'KN~\xaeHwP|\xd8\x06\xb4:\x14\n\x12\n\x10.mS\x01\xe4TB\xff\xa7V\xbf\xce\x0bM\xc6\xa9:\x14\n\x12\n\x10y\x05\x98S\x06\xd8H\x86\x9b06I\xefX\x82\x12:\x14\n\x12\n\x10\'\xb0;0I\x0eK+\xac\xa9\x95\xb5N\xcf,\x88:\x14\n\x12\n\x10\xc5\xb0i\xf6\x8alK(\x81&i%~U\x01\xf9J\x10british invasionJ\x0cclassic rockJ\nmerseybeatJ\x10psychedelic rockJ\x04rockb\xc6\xd2\x01\n\xcd\x8b\x01The Beatles recorded together for a little over seven years. Between October 1962 and May 1970, they released thirteen albums and a number of tracks issued on standalone singles. The catalogue created in that short period has sold more than that of any other group in history and its commercial success continues - the world\xe2\x80\x99s best selling album during the first decade of the 21st century was a collection of The Beatles\xe2\x80\x99 chart-topping singles called 1. But the group\xe2\x80\x99s significance stems not just from huge sales figures. Their music has inspired generation upon generation of musicians, songwriters and producers. As Mark Ronson put it: \xe2\x80\x98Everything we take for granted - they absolutely invented it.\xe2\x80\x99 Tom Petty was a teenager during the years The Beatles\xe2\x80\x99 records appeared in quick succession: \xe2\x80\x98They were just out in front. There was The Beatles \xe2\x80\xa6and then there was everyone else. And everyone else could be great, but The Beatles were leading the way and that\xe2\x80\x99s just irrefutably true.\xe2\x80\x99\n\n\n\nThe Beatles\xe2\x80\x99 story began in Liverpool in March 1957, when <a href=""spotify:artist:4x1nvY2FN8jxqAFA0DA02H"">John Lennon</a> (born 9 October 1940) formed a group named The Quarry Men. His life was changed by the excitement of rock \xe2\x80\x99n\xe2\x80\x99 roll music - heralded by Bill Haley and His Comets, but taken to another level when Elvis Presley stormed the charts during 1956. The next year saw the arrival in the UK of hits by Little Richard, Buddy Holly and The Crickets, the Everly Brothers and, in movie theatres, the exciting rock film The Girl Can\xe2\x80\x99t Help It!, featuring Eddie Cochran singing \xe2\x80\x98Twenty Flight Rock\xe2\x80\x99. Introduced to John on 6 July 1957 at a church fete in Woolton, Liverpool, <a href=""spotify:artist:4STHEaNw4mPZ2tzheohgXB"">Paul McCartney</a> (born 18 June 1942) sang Eddie\xe2\x80\x99s song word perfect. Impressed, John invited the fifteen-year old to join his group. In February 1958, Paul\xe2\x80\x99s younger school pal <a href=""spotify:artist:7FIoB5PHdrMZVC3q2HE5MS"">George Harrison</a> (born 25 February 1943) won his place in The Quarry Men when he impressed the others with his guitar skills, especially on the current hit instrumental \xe2\x80\x98Raunchy\xe2\x80\x99 by Bill Justis. With a constant nucleus of John, Paul and George, the group underwent a series of line-up changes and names. Having gained a dependable drummer - Pete Best - in August 1960, The Beatles made their first visit to West Germany to perform in the clubs of Hamburg. Playing long sets through the night, they spent hundreds of hours onstage during five visits to the city. Back home in Liverpool, their regular stomping ground was The Cavern Club, where they played nearly 300 times. The experience gained in Hamburg and at The Cavern helped to make The Beatles the most proficient and popular group on Merseyside.\n\n\n\nAt this time, a group from Liverpool had the odds stacked against them when trying to gain a foothold in a record business focused on London. In early 1962, they had acquired an ambitious and rather refined manager, record shop boss Brian Epstein. He faced regular rejection from music companies until George Martin signed the group to EMI\xe2\x80\x99s Parlophone label. By fate, The Beatles had found both the ideal manager and perfect producer. The last piece of the picture slotted into place just three weeks before recording their first single on 4 September 1962. <a href=""spotify:artist:6DbJi8AcN5ANdtvJcwBSw8"">Ringo Starr</a> (born 7 July 1940) was asked to take over as drummer. He had been playing with Rory Storm & The Hurricanes - another Liverpool group who played long stints in the clubs of Hamburg. Ringo\xe2\x80\x99s personality, sense of humour and rock solid, inventive drumming proved to be just right for The Beatles. Their first Parlophone single was released on 5 October 1962. Both sides of the disc were original compositions - a remarkable statement of intent from a group making their first steps in the music business. In fact, George Martin had urged them to record Mitch Murray\xe2\x80\x99s \xe2\x80\x98How Do You Do It?\xe2\x80\x99, which he felt was a sure-fire hit. They had reluctantly agreed, but were able to persuade George to shelve the recording in favour of their own songs \xe2\x80\x98Love Me Do\xe2\x80\x99 and \xe2\x80\x98P.S. I Love You\xe2\x80\x99. Just one example of how The Beatles\xe2\x80\x99 story might have been very different with a less open-minded record producer. George Martin\xe2\x80\x99s faith in The Beatles, and in John and Paul as songwriters, was soon vindicated by the release of \xe2\x80\x98Please Please Me\xe2\x80\x99 in January 1963. The single reached the top of all but one of the UK charts.  \n\n\n\nIt was followed by the number one \xe2\x80\x98From Me To You\xe2\x80\x99 and their first album Please Please Me, which topped the chart for 30 weeks until their next LP replaced it at number one. The debut album featured eight Lennon/McCartney compositions and six cover versions of recent American Rhythm and Blues records. The selection, a result of The Beatles\xe2\x80\x99 constant search for the unusual, showed their impeccable taste. Compared to the sophisticated arrangement of an R&B original like \xe2\x80\x98Twist And Shout\xe2\x80\x99, their versions were stripped down reinventions for a four-piece beat group. George Martin has confirmed that \xe2\x80\x98it was primarily the American Rhythm and Blues sound that was their inspiration. It\xe2\x80\x99s probably what the so-called Beatles sound was, because all the black music was a tremendous influence on them.\xe2\x80\x99 However, that source was unknown to the majority of their British fans. The super-confident second album With The Beatles was issued in November 1963 when the single \xe2\x80\x98She Loves You\xe2\x80\x99 was at number one. Once more, it featured eight original compositions - including \xe2\x80\x98All My Loving\xe2\x80\x99 and George Harrison\xe2\x80\x99s first recorded song \xe2\x80\x98Don\xe2\x80\x99t Bother Me\xe2\x80\x99 - and six cover versions. A week later, \xe2\x80\x98I Want To Hold Your Hand\xe2\x80\x99 was released and also reached number one. The group had become the biggest musical phenomenon in British show business - ever. Among the key factors that led to this success were the chemistry between the four personalities in the group, their immense charm and a daring image - nobody had worn their hair that long. Their interviews were funny and articulate, they had a charismatic presence when performing, and girls screamed and swooned over them. The term \xe2\x80\x98Beatlemania\xe2\x80\x99 was coined by the press to describe the hysteria aroused by the group but, as an appearance on The Royal Variety Show demonstrated, their popularity stretched way beyond the teenage market.\n\n\n\nWhat The Beatles did next was extraordinary for a British act. In February 1964, they arrived in the USA to appear on the Ed Sullivan Show. They performed to 73 million viewers, the biggest television audience to date, and with \xe2\x80\x98I Want To Hold Your Hand\xe2\x80\x99 at the top of the charts, America was suddenly held spellbound by The Beatles. As their success spread across the world, almost everything the group did from then on was unprecedented. In addition to unparalleled success on record - they held all top five positions in the American chart in the first week of April - their first movie A Hard Day\xe2\x80\x99s Night was a box office hit and acclaimed for its wit, invention and unbeatable self-composed songs. Premiered in July 1964, it was perfectly timed to capitalise on their international breakthrough. They rounded off the year with Beatles For Sale and the massive hit single \xe2\x80\x98I Feel Fine\xe2\x80\x99. In 1965, they starred in the film Help!. Like their first movie, it was directed by Richard Lester and featured a brilliant batch of songs on its accompanying album. Tucked away towards the end of the LP was a performance by Paul McCartney of his composition \xe2\x80\x98Yesterday\xe2\x80\x99. Not even released as a single in the UK, it was a number one in America. It quickly became - and remains - the most covered song of all time. \n\n\n\n\xe2\x80\x98Yesterday\xe2\x80\x99 is an example of how The Beatles and their producer did not compromise; whatever best served the song was always pursued. In the case of \xe2\x80\x98Yesterday\xe2\x80\x99, the bold choice was a classical arrangement for string quartet. For the next album Rubber Soul, more studio time was made available to try out unusual instrumentation and adventurous recording techniques. The words of the songs were more mature and the vocal blend, heard on tracks such as \xe2\x80\x98Nowhere Man\xe2\x80\x99 and \xe2\x80\x98Michelle\xe2\x80\x99, is one of the album\xe2\x80\x99s most distinctive qualities. The Beatles\xe2\x80\x99 sound is, of course, distinguished by the character of their voices. Few groups were blessed with two powerful lead singers as versatile as John Lennon and Paul McCartney. Furthermore, George Harrison not only contributed at least one lead vocal to every album, his voice was integral to the intricate harmony vocals on many Beatles tracks. Ringo Starr usually sang a solo on albums, making such Lennon/McCartney songs as \xe2\x80\x98Yellow Submarine\xe2\x80\x99 and \xe2\x80\x98With A Little Help From My Friends\xe2\x80\x99 unimaginable without his voice.\n\n\n\nReleased on the same day as Rubber Soul, 5 December 1965, \xe2\x80\x98We Can Work It Out\xe2\x80\x99/\xe2\x80\x98Day Tripper\xe2\x80\x99 was the first of The Beatles\xe2\x80\x99 double A-Sides. They ended another frantically busy year with their final British tour. There was a deadline to complete their next album, because concerts had been scheduled for the summer of 1966 all over the world. But this did not affect their approach to recording at all. The Revolver sessions saw the group reach a new peak of creativity in performance, songwriting and innovative studio techniques. In addition to the songwriting mastery displayed by John and Paul, the LP contained the biggest contribution to date from George with three songs. His caustic \xe2\x80\x98Taxman\xe2\x80\x99 was given the status of the album\xe2\x80\x99s opening track. \xe2\x80\x98Eleanor Rigby\xe2\x80\x99 is now regarded as a fully realised masterpiece, but when released in August 1966 on Revolver and as a single coupled with \xe2\x80\x98Yellow Submarine\xe2\x80\x99, its solemn subject matter and stark arrangement were radically different. A year before, in August 1965, their appearance in front of 55,600 fans at Shea Stadium in New York had broken the record for concert attendance and box-office revenue. But live performance had become an unsatisfying charade ...and dangerous too. Who cares how lucrative it was? That had to stop. The Beatles\xe2\x80\x99 final concert for a paying audience took place at Candlestick Park, San Francisco on 29 August 1966.\n\n\n\nAt the end of 1966, The Beatles started work on \xe2\x80\x98Strawberry Fields Forever\xe2\x80\x99. Its long evolution showed the musical imagination and technical experimentation heard on Revolver would be continued. To stop the long wait for new material, \xe2\x80\x98Strawberry Fields Forever\xe2\x80\x99 and \xe2\x80\x98Penny Lane\xe2\x80\x99 were released in February 1967. Although songs were always credited to Lennon and McCartney, it soon became clear that whoever sang the lead vocal was usually the main composer. The double A-sided single shows how their different stylistic approaches established a perfect counterbalance. Having set themselves a task of writing about their Liverpool childhoods, John\xe2\x80\x99s song is dreamy and steeped in melancholy, while Paul\xe2\x80\x99s is uplifting and brimming with brilliantly observed vignettes. Many were shocked when the unconventional promotional films for both songs were broadcast. Even their moustaches and John\xe2\x80\x99s spectacles were considered to be evidence of how weird The Beatles had become. The square world worried. Everyone else listened over and over until they \xe2\x80\x98got it\xe2\x80\x99. Released on 1 June 1967, the immediate artistic and commercial success of Sgt. Pepper\xe2\x80\x99s Lonely Hearts Club Band vindicated the new approach taken by The Beatles. It was the album that provided the soundtrack to the so-called \xe2\x80\x98summer of love\xe2\x80\x99, but its appeal is ageless. The Beatles performed their next single \xe2\x80\x98All You Need Is Love\xe2\x80\x99 for the first time on the TV programme Our World - broadcast live to an audience of 350 million around the globe. Their place at the top of contemporary pop music was indisputable. Sadly, soon afterwards, The Beatles were shaken by the sudden death of their manager Brian Epstein in August 1967. They rallied to write and direct Magical Mystery Tour - a film shown on television in the UK at Christmas. Some of the millions who saw it, did not like it. As Paul McCartney remembered: \xe2\x80\x98They were looking for the plum-pudding special. That\xe2\x80\x99s what they were expecting, and they very much didn\xe2\x80\x99t get it! We were giving it to the young kids. Why shouldn\xe2\x80\x99t they see something far out?\xe2\x80\x99 The music was as successful as ever. The six new songs in the film and the number one \xe2\x80\x98Hello, Goodbye\xe2\x80\x99 completed a momentous year of recording. Three more tracks from 1967 remained unreleased until they were heard in the movie Yellow Submarine premiered in 1968. The film\xe2\x80\x99s imaginative animation evoked the \xe2\x80\x98psychedelic\xe2\x80\x99 spirit of Sgt. Pepper to reveal the triumph of Love over Evil.\n\n\n\nNowadays, following a year as busy as The Beatles had in 1967, an artist would take an extended break. In fact, the group did allow themselves a little time off. The first music of 1968 came in March on their seventeenth single \xe2\x80\x98Lady Madonna\xe2\x80\x99. Soon after it was recorded, The Beatles flew to Rishikesh, India for several weeks of meditation with Maharishi Mahesh Yogi. At this remote and peaceful location, they enjoyed a prolific period of songwriting. As George Harrison explained: \xe2\x80\x98When we came back, it became apparent that there were more songs than would make up a single album.\xe2\x80\x99 Recorded in five months, the double LP The Beatles was soon known as \xe2\x80\x98The White Album\xe2\x80\x99 because of its plain white cover. \xe2\x80\x98Hey Jude\xe2\x80\x99 and \xe2\x80\x98Revolution\xe2\x80\x99 were the first songs to be heard from the sessions when they were released as a single on 30 August 1968 - the first Beatles record to be pressed with the Apple label. Never interested in repeating themselves, The Beatles took a different approach in the studio in 1968. Ringo Starr remembered: \xe2\x80\x98On \xe2\x80\x9cThe White Album\xe2\x80\x9d we ended up being a band again and that\xe2\x80\x99s what I always love. I love being in a band.\xe2\x80\x99 Discussing his songwriting, John Lennon reflected: \xe2\x80\x98It was a complete reversal from Sgt. Pepper. My songs on the double album were fairly simple and basic.\xe2\x80\x99 It is still astonishing to hear The Beatles moving through every style of popular music imaginable, including a pastiche of a Hollywood musical number (\xe2\x80\x98Honey Pie\xe2\x80\x99), an intense blues (\xe2\x80\x98Yer Blues\xe2\x80\x99) and heavy rock (\xe2\x80\x98Helter Skelter\xe2\x80\x99). As with Sgt. Pepper, no singles were released from \xe2\x80\x98The White Album\xe2\x80\x99 in the UK and USA during the 1960s. But it is full of tracks that could have been huge hits, such as \xe2\x80\x98Back In The USSR\xe2\x80\x99, \xe2\x80\x98Ob-la-di, Ob-la-da\xe2\x80\x99 and \xe2\x80\x98While My Guitar Gently Weeps\xe2\x80\x99.\n\n\n\nIn January 1969, while \xe2\x80\x98The White Album\xe2\x80\x99 was still at number one, The Beatles assembled to write and rehearse brand new songs for a televised live concert. The plan changed so that, in the end, their work was documented in a movie released over a year later. Its final scene showed The Beatles performing on the roof of their Apple office building in Savile Row, London with most of the audience gathered in the street below. \xe2\x80\x98Get Back\xe2\x80\x99, a number one single from the sessions at Apple, was swiftly followed by \xe2\x80\x98The Ballad Of John And Yoko\xe2\x80\x99 - a chronicle of John\xe2\x80\x99s marriage to Yoko Ono and their honeymoon/\xe2\x80\x98Bed-In\xe2\x80\x99 for peace in Amsterdam. Recorded mostly during t\x01\x00\x01:\xafhe summer of 1969, the last album The Beatles made together was named after the street where EMI\xe2\x80\x99s studios are located. It was a fitting tribute to the place where the majority of their songs had been recorded. The Beatles\xe2\x80\x99 collaboration with producer George Martin and the engineers at Abbey Road had challenged the way that popular music was created. On many occasions this team re-wrote the rule book and set a new standard to which their contemporaries had to aspire. In contrast to the January recordings at Apple, which were \xe2\x80\x98as live\xe2\x80\x99 with no overdubs, their return to Abbey Road studios with George Martin resulted in carefully crafted tracks with ambitious musical arrangements. The album\xe2\x80\x99s varied highlights include \xe2\x80\x98Come Together\xe2\x80\x99 and two songs that showed George Harrison\xe2\x80\x99s songwriting had hit a peak - \xe2\x80\x98Something\xe2\x80\x99 and \xe2\x80\x98Here Comes The Sun\xe2\x80\x99. However, the character of Abbey Road is dominated by the sophisticated medley the group called \xe2\x80\x98The Long One\xe2\x80\x99. It brought the album, and The Beatles\xe2\x80\x99 recording career, to an impressive conclusion. What a farewell. Measured in terms of its enormous popularity and musical ingenuity, Abbey Road now challenges the status of Sgt. Pepper Lonely Hearts Club Band as The Beatles\xe2\x80\x99 greatest achievement. When the earlier set of recordings from 1969 was finally released as Let It Be in May 1970, news had already broken that the group had split up. The album\xe2\x80\x99s title track and \xe2\x80\x98The Long And Winding Road\xe2\x80\x99 took the total of American number ones by The Beatles to twenty in six years - a feat unequalled by any other artist.\n\n\n\nWhen The Beatles began making records, no one anticipated that they would be listened to far into the future. Pop music was regarded as disposable. But the timeless appeal of The Beatles\xe2\x80\x99 catalogue ensured it was built to last and highly valued. In 1979, the distinguished conductor and composer Leonard Bernstein wrote: \xe2\x80\x98Three bars of \xe2\x80\x9cA Day In The Life\xe2\x80\x9d still sustain me, rejuvenate me, inflame my senses and sensibilities.\xe2\x80\x99 There is also another dimension to the seductive power of The Beatles\xe2\x80\x99 music. Filled with the spirit of the era in which it was born, it is joyous and generous. \xe2\x80\x98All You Need Is Love\xe2\x80\x99. \xe2\x80\x98With our love - we could save the world.\xe2\x80\x99 \xe2\x80\x98The love you take is equal to the love you make.\xe2\x80\x99 Tom Petty felt it: \xe2\x80\x98We grew up with The Beatles and grew up trusting them. They could have chosen to do anything and they chose to do good, which is a great example for the rest of us.\xe2\x80\x99\n\n\n\nKevin Howlett\n\n\x1a\x80\x01\n\x1e\n\x14\x7f\xe1\xa6\x93\xad\xc5.\'Ib\xf1\xc6\x1dv\xca\x9c\xccb\xc1\x91\x10\x00\x18\x90\x03 \xe2\r\n\x1e\n\x14\xc0\xe0.4\x13\xd5cZ\xdf\x8e\x88\xcbK;\x88\xde\x06>X<\x10\x03\x18\xd0\x0f \xc2\x15\x1a\x80\x01\n\x1e\n\x14\x93/\xc7\x8fX\xf3\xba\xf0\xaa\x91\xf9\xfb:\x00\x97\x0f\xf0,H\xa0\x10\x00\x18\x90\x03 \xc4\r\n\x1e\n\x14\xab\x01^\xa8z\x84\x04\xc2\xd2\xac\xa9\xc5\x87-f\xb3\xe2\xeb\x9f\x93\x10\x03\x18\xd0\x0f T\n\x1e\n\x14$2\xc8\xcd\x00h\xe8ar\'HXZ\x87Q~\xc1\x92\r\x8a\x10\x02\x18\x80\n \xce\x06\n\x1e\n\x14\xa3t\x8d\xa7z\x05\xdaR\n-o\x1c\x98]>X\xed\x8a\xe5\xf4\x10\x03\x18\xd0\x0f \xda\x17\x1a\x7f\n\x1e\n\x14T\x19\xa8\x84\x01g\xeed\xfa\x87`\xc5\x83\x05b\xbd0o;\xe4\x10\x00\x18\x90\x03 \xe8\t\n\x1e\n\x14X\xfa(|&\x0bU\xfa\x95\xf9\xb2\x12MW\xcc6;\xd6\xfa\xae\x10\x03\x18\xd0\x0f \xac\x0f\x1a\x7f\n\x1e\n\x14O\xa7\x9c\xb6\x7f\xc6\\I\x99\xf3\xd6\'\x18\xae.r\\q,\xe0\x10\x00\x18\x90\x03 \xa8\r\n\x1e\n\x14\x818(\xba\n\x1c\xf2e9>\xff4vJ\xf2L\xc0?\t\x14\x10\x03\x18\xd0\x0f \xe8\x14\x1a\x80\x01\n\x1e\n\x14\xbeuf\x81\xb8\xb2\xab\xcd\xbfE\x19\xd3\xc7j\xf6%\xc0\x03y\xba\x10\x00\x18\x90\x03 \xd0\x0b\n\x1e\n\x14\xd5\x8c\x8cV}:\xbf\xc7Q:\xef\xc0\x8faJ\x88\x0fh\x03[\x10\x03\x18\xd0\x0f \x96\x12\x1a\x7f\n\x1e\n\x14\x14/_9\x16\x16\xc3m\xe1\x1c5\xf5I\xacdv\x1b\xa5\xe9\xa2\x10\x00\x18\x90\x03 X\n\x1e\n\x147\x94\x05oV:\xfa\xc1\xf0*Rj\x15=]\xb6T\x92hs\x10\x02\x18\x80\n \xea\x06\n\x1e\n\x14\xab\x9c\xbe\xca\x89\xbfL<.[\xfbz\xd7)\x98\xf5\x8f\xaa)\xae\x10\x03\x18\xd0\x0f \xef.\xa1\x972\x14\n\x12\n\x10\x82\xf5\xe0Q\x9c\x89C\x19\xb4\xf05\x96\x05\xdf\xe4\xb62\x14\n\x12\n\x10\x17P\x7f(\x13\xc4O%\x9f\x90-\x9d\x14\xcb\xf1D2\x14\n\x12\n\x10 \xce_\xd8\x9e\x1cI3\x88W\xbd\x16\xeeB\xc3\xad2\x14\n\x12\n\x10\x063\x81>u\xadIv\x83\x9fF\x14\x86I\xeed2\x14\n\x12\n\x10a%\xcf<\x9e\x05@\xe8\x98\x18\x07kVX\x0f\xc52\x14\n\x12\n\x10\xa0\xaa\xa2\xbdJmF\xdc\xa0\x88P\x9f\x8cr`)2\x14\n\x12\n\x10\x93\x18\xe4wA\x85C&\x97O\xc6\xc6\xcc:\x9c\x7f2\x14\n\x12\n\x10\x8dg\x87%\r\xe5M\'\xb1\x9c\xcbN\x95\x8fY\x84B\x14\n\x12\n\x10/7\xc6\xc20\x01F\xb7\xb5G.U1\x97\x95\x03B\x14\n\x12\n\x10\xd3\xc7\x8a\x97\xcf#@\x7f\x98\xcbj\x04\x03\x9e\xcefB\x14\n\x12\n\x10\xaex*\r;~K\xeb\x8e\x98|\x82\xf86\x8e\xddB\x14\n\x12\n\x10\xcf\x05\xd0?\xd7\xf8D\x1f\xabL\xb7f\x17,I\xc7B\x14\n\x12\n\x10\x9b\xbfp\xb4\x13mA\xd6\xa2^\x11G\x9e?\xec\xfcB\x14\n\x12\n\x10F,{\xc0\xb7\xc9F\xda\x9e\xb3\x879%\xedreB\x14\n\x12\n\x10r\t\xc6\x9cV\xffI6\xb6K\x9aw\x15\xef>\xf7B\x14\n\x12\n\x10\xa9l\xc5\x925\xd5I\xa4\xbc\xd2\xd0\x02\x91\xfa\xf5\xe2B\x14\n\x12\n\x10SC\xf3\x1d\x95JA:\xa6\xdf\x0c\xb1>j\x85\xbfB\x14\n\x12\n\x10&\'#2hjC;\xa0C\xc5m\x00\x90\xbb\xc0B(\n\x12\n\x10\\\x8c\x86\xf8\xf83J\x1e\x84\x9cN)\x08\x91@|\n\x12\n\x10\x96\xa0\x10\x82u\xf5C\xc5\x83\x98\xeaD\x96\xef>WB(\n\x12\n\x10\x92\x1a/\xfe\xc5\x9cGw\xb4\xe0\x12R\x87\xfc\xfdE\n\x12\n\x10\xef\xd2\'\x94\x8dtOD\xb18?I\x8e-vSB\x14\n\x12\n\x10\x8a4Z\x94\x7f\xf9MN\xa6B\n\xc2Hm\x19sB\x14\n\x12\n\x10\xe7p\x8at\x8c\xf1A\x1c\x9ap\xc1d\x90]\x04\xcdB\x14\n\x12\n\x10\x16\xa1dL\x02\xfeC\xca\xb5\x98\xfd; \xe8S\xbdB\x14\n\x12\n\x10\xb7\x81x}\xae\x07K\xce\x9e\xd2\xa4\x13\x19\x8a\xfd\x9fB\x14\n\x12\n\x10|\xf8r\xde\x0e\xf8G\x83\xb1\xda\r\xc5\x19\x96\xaf7B\x14\n\x12\n\x10\xae\xcc\xe0\x9d_hC\x08\x87\x8b\x9fl^\x84Q<B\x14\n\x12\n\x10)\x19\xc3:\xe9LO\xbc\x8f=\xcfA$\xa0R\xbeB\x14\n\x12\n\x10\xd9@\xfb\xf8VzO\x98\x98\x8f\xc8\'\xb0m-\xc5B\x14\n\x12\n\x10\x05\xf5S\xba\x01\x81O\x8f\x94l]\xe1\xb5;~""B\x14\n\x12\n\x10\xc6\'\xdf\xffm\x12L\xa0\x97+-3]\xb6\xed\xbfB\x14\n\x12\n\x10o\xddx\x83\x958C\x07\x8c5\x8f\x12\xf9\x08\xcc\xb8B\x14\n\x12\n\x10\xe6\'~j\xc5\xf5E\xb0\x88\x01M\xdd\xfaoa\xe7B\x14\n\x12\n\x10l\xd4\xe0\xdf\xbcl@\xad\x9e\n\xb5(\xbdoZ\xe6J\x07electroJ\x0cfilter houseb\x884\n\xf9-Even as they evolved from French house pioneers in the \'90s to dance tastemakers in the 2000s to mainstream heroes in the 2010s, Daft Punk remained one of dance music\'s most influential and iconic acts. The combined talents of Guy-Manuel de Homem-Christo and <a href=""spotify:artist:41vv2Tj1knysv6MuFUmdwi"">Thomas Bangalter</a>, the Parisian duo quickly won acclaim for their unique blend of first-wave acid house and techno with pop, indie rock, and hip-hop. One of the pair\'s first projects together was <a href=""spotify:artist:1sLvmWlA2BEuwykAtv6PF8"">Darling</a>, an instrumental indie cover band; their current recording name derives from a review in U.K. music weekly <a href=""spotify:search:label%3A%22Melody+Maker%22"">Melody Maker</a> of a compilation tape <a href=""spotify:artist:1sLvmWlA2BEuwykAtv6PF8"">Darling</a> were featured on, released by Krautrock revivalists <a href=""spotify:artist:3Rj0tDHoX7C5NFq5DKIpHt"">Stereolab</a> (their lo-fi D.I.Y. cover of a <a href=""spotify:artist:3oDbviiivRWhXwIE8hxkVV"">Beach Boys</a> song was derided as ""daft punk""). Subsequently ditching the almost inevitable creative cul-de-sac of rock for the more appealing rush of the dancefloor, the pair released their debut single, ""The New Wave,"" in 1993 on the celebrated <a href=""spotify:search:label%3A%22Soma%22"">Soma</a> label. Instantly hailed by the dance music press as the work of a new breed of house innovators, the single was followed by ""Da Funk,"" the band\'s first true hit (the record sold 30,000 copies worldwide and saw thorough rinsings by everyone from <a href=""spotify:artist:4oHDMGLufm0nUeo0ITiWl1"">Kris Needs</a> to <a href=""spotify:artist:1GhPHrq36VKCY3ucVaZCfo"">the Chemical Brothers</a>).\r\n\nAlthough the group had only released a trio of singles (""The New Wave"" and ""Da Funk,"" as well as the 1996 limited pressing of ""Musique""), in early 1996 Daft Punk were the subject of a minor bidding war. The group eventually signed with <a href=""spotify:search:label%3A%22Virgin%22"">Virgin</a>, with its first long-player, Homework, appearing early the following year (a brief preview of the album, ""Musique,"" was also featured on the <a href=""spotify:search:label%3A%22Virgin%22"">Virgin</a> compilation Wipeout XL next to tracks from <a href=""spotify:artist:3hXDMlrPegHRO0zUvBsRSI"">Photek</a>, <a href=""spotify:artist:2qhmNI4ZHPpeDutdg473Z3"">Future Sound of London</a>, <a href=""spotify:artist:1GhPHrq36VKCY3ucVaZCfo"">the Chemical Brothers</a>, and <a href=""spotify:artist:0fo0tocXO4ZkkVn3L0VZzB"">Source Direct</a>). As with the earlier singles, the group\'s sound is a brazen, dancefloor-oriented blend of progressive house, funk, electro, and techno, with sprinklings of hip-hop-styled breakbeats and excessive, crowd-firing samples similar to other anthemic dance-fusion acts such as <a href=""spotify:artist:1GhPHrq36VKCY3ucVaZCfo"">the Chemical Brothers</a> and <a href=""spotify:artist:2skPJYe0WOmOU76qTWjK8B"">Monkey Mafia</a>. In addition to his role in Daft Punk, <a href=""spotify:artist:41vv2Tj1knysv6MuFUmdwi"">Bangalter</a> operates the <a href=""spotify:search:label%3A%22Roul%C3%A9%22"">Roul\xc3\xa9</a> label and has recorded under his own name (the underground smash ""Trax on da Rocks"") as well as <a href=""spotify:artist:2XCRceysrNlpv5a1kTm4Hm"">Stardust</a> (the huge club/commercial hit ""Music Sounds Better with You""). \r\n\nAfter four long years of fans eagerly awaiting a follow-up to their brilliant debut, Daft Punk finally issued Discovery in March 2001. The live record Alive 1997 followed at the end of the year, and a by-now predictable four-year wait preceded the release of Human After All in early 2005. One year later, Daft Punk released a compilation, Musique, Vol. 1: 1993-2005, and in 2007 their second live record, Alive 2007, arrived. The album and its single ""Harder, Better, Faster, Stronger"" won Grammy Awards early in 2009; shortly after, it was announced that the duo would compose the soundtrack to Tron: Legacy, the sequel to the 1982 classic sci-fi film Tron. Daft Punk\'s music for the movie was released in November 2010, shortly before the film -- which featured the group in a cameo -- arrived in theaters. \r\n\nEarly in 2013, Daft Punk announced that they planned to have a new album released by May of that year. That March, the duo announced the album\'s title, Random Access Memories, and also launched an extensive press campaign featuring snippets of the album\'s lead single, ""Get Lucky,"" and interviews with some of their collaborators (<a href=""spotify:artist:3yDIp0kaq9EFKe07X1X2rz"">Nile Rodgers</a>, <a href=""spotify:artist:3f626JSVauIhTQgatsFcs4"">Paul Williams</a>, <a href=""spotify:artist:6jU2Tt13MmXYk0ZBv1KmfO"">Giorgio Moroder</a>, <a href=""spotify:artist:1R84VlXnFFULOsWWV8IrCQ"">Panda Bear</a>). The single was officially released in April, and Random Access Memories arrived in May. The album became one of Daft Punk\'s biggest successes, ultimately winning Grammy Awards for Best Dance/Electronica Album, Album of the Year, and Best Engineered Album, Non-Classical. ""Get Lucky"" earned Grammys for Best Pop Duo/Group Performance and Record of the Year. In 2014, the duo appeared on <a href=""spotify:artist:2RdwBSPQiwcmiDo9kixcl8"">Pharrell</a>\'s album G I R L and collaborated with <a href=""spotify:artist:3nFkdlSjzX9mRTtwJOzDYB"">Jay-Z</a> on the song ""Computerized."" A 2015 documentary titled Daft Punk Unchained charted their history from the \'90s into the 2010s, featuring interviews with <a href=""spotify:artist:3yDIp0kaq9EFKe07X1X2rz"">Rodgers</a>, <a href=""spotify:artist:2RdwBSPQiwcmiDo9kixcl8"">Pharrell</a>, and <a href=""spotify:artist:5K4W6rqBFWDnAN6FQUkS6x"">Kanye West</a>, among others. The duo remained active, collaborating next with <a href=""spotify:artist:1Xyo4u8uXC1ZmMpatF05PJ"">the Weeknd</a>\'s Abel Tesfaye on a pair of songs from his 2016 album Starboy, including the number one hit title track. ~ Sean Cooper, Rovi\x1a\x80\x01\n\x1e\n\x14\xab~\xb5\xc6\x986\xf3\xd7\xa1$\xf4\xc8\x8dB\xbd\x8aKn\x12{\x10\x00\x18\x90\x03 \xde\x0b\x1a\x80\x01\n\x1e\n\x14\xca\x02i\x86\xdd\xc5x\x0b\x05`2\xd4\xcb\x164\xc1\xdd\xed:q\x10\x00\x18\x90\x03 \x90\x03\n\x1e\n\x14<\x9fU\xdc\x0f\x1b\xd70Mk^\xc4\xc9SGg\x11)\xc0\xfa\x10\x01\x18\x80\x01 \x80\x01\n\x1e\n\x14\xb1\xdat\xb8\x9d<\x9b\x18\xf3\xe2\x85\x0c*\x86\xc5\xa5 \x16W\x05\x10\x02\x18\x80\n \x98\x17\xab\xa52\x14\n\x12\n\x10\x90bn\xd5\xa9aD\xce\x9bK=>\x1f\xebJ,:\x14\n\x12\n\x10+\x8b\x13\x169\xc4M\xaf\x95H\xed\x91\xef\xbbE\xdeB\x14\n\x12\n\x10\'\xf9u\xea\xa2\x05N\x11\xa8\xe6\xd0\x82\xc9\x8cB\xa3B\x14\n\x12\n\x10Z\x80b\xf7\x8f*C\xf7\x9bW\xde\xed\xbf\xf7\xf2\x90B\x14\n\x12\n\x10\xd5eY]\xd8mD{\x9eU\x8c\xcd!f\xf6\xb4B\x14\n\x12\n\x10$\x0c\xb7\xea\xdcwJ\x82\x9bQR\xb9\xee\x8dL\xa6B\x14\n\x12\n\x10\xc5X\xe7p\xac\xf9N\x99\x97\x97\x01\x03\t\xe2g\xbeB\x14\n\x12\n\x10\xe7\x07#\xe0J_F\x7f\x82n+x\x95\x12\xce\x84B\x14\n\x12\n\x10\x18\x9a\xb5\x9f\xfa\x04@\xa3\xbb\xc4\xbd\x16\x93\n\x1b\xaaB\x14\n\x12\n\x10=\xca\xafm\xd1xF\xa2\x8b\x81CF\x00\xbc\xee""B\x14\n\x12\n\x10\x8c\x99g\xa3\x12\xedAk\xb8k\xc5 EV\xf3\x91B\x14\n\x12\n\x10\x87\xee#\xd6\x85\x13I\x88\xb7\xdd\xec\xde\xb5b\x83\xe4B\x14\n\x12\n\x10\xf1\x17\xb9\xbb\x9d\x81Mh\x90\xb3F""\xdf\x83\xd4\xc0B\x14\n\x12\n\x10#\xc1l-n\xf3F,\xbe[\xdc\x16G\x87\xbc%B\x14\n\x12\n\x10\x81\xd6S1\xbd\xdfD3\xa5\x15\x19\x19\xb7\xe4g\xfbB\x14\n\x12\n\x10\x8d`\x14\x04\xe1\x02G\x90\x82\xb4m\x08?\x90\x96\xafB\x14\n\x12\n\x10\xc0\x92\xe2\xc7L\x04I\x0f\x83\x0f\xa7?\x93\xd3UdB\x14\n\x12\n\x10F/\xf0k\xf5\xbdDr\xb2\x91(\xc3\x93\xa5\xd3\xd8B\x14\n\x12\n\x100\x81\x94\'9\x9dM\xf9\xac\xa9\x17^\x7f\xed\xb6\x8eB\x14\n\x12\n\x10\xc0n/\x9a\xe4\x90Eo\x83\xc9j\xf8u\xb2u1J\x08jam bandJ\nneo mellowJ\x08pop rockb\xc1E\n\xd4>Formed in the early \'90s by South African vocalist/guitarist <a href=""spotify:artist:13vQloYd6mP7V1mVwKJwS2"">Dave Matthews</a>, the Dave Matthews Band presented a more pop-oriented version of <a href=""spotify:artist:4TMHGUX5WI7OOm53PqSDAT"">the Grateful Dead</a> crossed with elements of jazz, funk, and the worldbeat explorations of <a href=""spotify:artist:2CvCyf1gEVhI0mX6aFXmVI"">Paul Simon</a> and <a href=""spotify:artist:0Ty63ceoRnnJKVEYP0VQpk"">Sting</a>. <a href=""spotify:artist:13vQloYd6mP7V1mVwKJwS2"">Matthews</a> populated the group with several Virginia-based musicians -- bassist Stefan Lessard, saxophonist Leroi Moore, violinist <a href=""spotify:artist:1G3GtzoiNKet6AqJO4njh5"">Boyd Tinsley</a>, drummer Carter Beauford, and short-lived keyboardist Peter Griesar -- and the band built up a strong word-of-mouth buzz by touring the country constantly, with special attention paid to college campuses. Griesar left the lineup in March 1993, but the Dave Matthews Band moved ahead in his absence, releasing the independent album Remember Two Things later that year and issuing a live EP, Recently, in 1994. After fielding offers from major labels, the band signed with <a href=""spotify:search:label%3A%22RCA%22"">RCA</a> and released the debut effort Under the Table and Dreaming in September 1994. By the following spring, the record had launched the hit single ""What Would You Say"" and sold over one million copies, thus setting the stage for an extremely successful career.\r\n\nA year and a half after the release of Under the Table and Dreaming, the record had sold over four million copies in the U.S. alone, propelled in part by the success of ""Ants Marching"" and ""Satellite."" The Dave Matthews Band responded by releasing 1996\'s Crash, which entered the charts at number two and quickly went platinum. The group spent the bulk of 1996 touring in support of the eclectic album, which reached multi-platinum status and spun off five successful singles, including the Grammy-nominated ""Crash into Me."" That same year, <a href=""spotify:artist:13vQloYd6mP7V1mVwKJwS2"">Matthews</a> launched an attack on bootleggers in conjunction with the federal government, targeting stores that were selling semi-legal discs of live performances. The efforts of <a href=""spotify:artist:13vQloYd6mP7V1mVwKJwS2"">Matthews</a>, his band, and his management resulted in an unprecedented crackdown on for-profit bootleggers in early 1997 -- with nearly all of the major foreign bootlegging companies placed under arrest by the United States -- thereby putting a moratorium on the entire underground industry. \r\n\nTo further combat the bootleggers, the Dave Matthews Band released an official double-disc live album, Live at Red Rocks 8.15.95, in the fall of 1997. It was an unexpected success, debuting at number three on the charts and selling a million copies within the first five months of its release. The live record paved the way for a string of future DMB concert recordings; it also drummed up support for the April 1998 release of Before These Crowded Streets, the group\'s most ambitious album to date. Another two-disc live effort, Listener Supported, followed one year later, and summer tours kept the band busy as the decade drew to a close. \r\n\nThe new millennium, however, saw the band returning to the studio with producer <a href=""spotify:artist:6sveRRN3txi4tuhQ6HQI2A"">Glen Ballard</a> to record a fourth studio album, Everyday, which was issued in February 2001. Although notable for its slick, mainstream-minded sound -- not to mention the presence of electric guitar, which <a href=""spotify:artist:13vQloYd6mP7V1mVwKJwS2"">Matthews</a> had never used on previous albums -- it was overshadowed by rumors of a darker album that had been recorded with <a href=""spotify:artist:7fGW0xHsS8qa4W9KeHOQqN"">Steve Lillywhite</a> in 2000. Although the original album was rejected, the band eventually chose songs from those sessions, re-recorded several others, and released the results in July 2002 as Busted Stuff. Its debut single, ""Where Are You Going,"" fared well on national radio, and the band rounded out 2002 with the release of Live at Folsom Field in November. \r\n\nSeveral years after releasing Live at Luther College, a concert album that did not feature his band, <a href=""spotify:artist:13vQloYd6mP7V1mVwKJwS2"">Dave Matthews</a> released his first proper solo album in 2003. The moody and brooding Some Devil was supported by a ""Dave Matthews & Friends"" tour -- the ""friends"" being <a href=""spotify:artist:3Felk6Y6jjU00yE1XTOqKZ"">Trey Anastasio</a>, Brady Blade, Tony Hall, Ray Paczkowski, and <a href=""spotify:artist:7rvkQK7ZqO34sKsWEXjz3R"">Tim Reynolds</a> -- and the album\'s chief single, ""Gravedigger,"" earned <a href=""spotify:artist:13vQloYd6mP7V1mVwKJwS2"">Matthews</a> a Grammy Award for Best Male Rock Vocal Performance. <a href=""spotify:artist:1G3GtzoiNKet6AqJO4njh5"">Boyd Tinsley</a> also released a solo album that year, but the Dave Matthews Band reconvened shortly thereafter, releasing two additional live albums (The Central Park Concert, The Gorge) and returning to the road in 2004. The bandmates also joined <a href=""spotify:artist:3eqjTLE0HfPfh78zjh6TqT"">Bruce Springsteen</a>\'s Vote for Change tour toward the end of the year, just as their mail-order-only DMB Live Trax series debuted. In early 2005, they launched a website that featured progress reports on their next album in the form of video footage, diaries, and soundbites. When the flawed Stand Up finally appeared in May, it was the band\'s first album of all-new material since 2001\'s Everyday. Like its three predecessors, Stand Up topped the charts, making DMB the only band other than <a href=""spotify:artist:51Blml2LZPmy7TTiAg47vQ"">U2</a> and <a href=""spotify:artist:2ye2Wgw4gimLv2eAKyk1NB"">Metallica</a> to score four consecutive number one albums. \r\n\nWeekend on the Rocks, another live set, followed Stand Up at the end of 2005, and a two-disc compilation entitled The Best of What\'s Around, Vol. 1 collected studio material and unreleased live recordings one year later. <a href=""spotify:artist:13vQloYd6mP7V1mVwKJwS2"">Matthews</a> and <a href=""spotify:artist:7rvkQK7ZqO34sKsWEXjz3R"">Tim Reynolds</a> launched another joint tour in 2007, canvassing Europe and North America in the process. A performance from the latter continent was featured on the album Live at Radio City Music Hall, which served as a companion piece to 1999\'s Luther College. Meanwhile, the Dave Matthews Band released their own concert album, Live at Piedmont Park, and began working on new material, although the project was temporarily shelved during pre-production as the band diverted its focus to touring. \r\n\nThe musicians returned to the studio the following year, but LeRoi Moore unfortunately passed away before the record could be completed. The saxophonist had suffered a serious ATV accident in June and ultimately succumbed to his injuries two months later. Former <a href=""spotify:artist:2ka8z2lwkcp13fG8Wyv3xU"">B\xc3\xa9la Fleck</a> saxophonist <a href=""spotify:artist:0nQtFR0hKvnxrmBydLJt5D"">Jeff Coffin</a> joined in his place, and the band heralded his inclusion with the release of Live at the Mile High Music Festival, a three-disc set capturing a Colorado performance from that summer. Early the following year, the Dave Matthews Band paid tribute to Moore with the release of Big Whiskey & the GrooGrux King. The three-CD/one-DVD set Europe 2009, which chronicled a July 5, 2009 show in Lucca, Italy (CD) and a June 26, 2009 show at O2 Academy Brixton in London (DVD) arrived in December 2009. Additional performances were documented on 2010\'s Live in New York City and 2011\'s Live at Wrigley Field, the latter of which was released during the band\'s 20th anniversary. The Dave Matthews Band\'s seventh studio album, Away from the World, released in 2012, found them reuniting with producer <a href=""spotify:artist:7fGW0xHsS8qa4W9KeHOQqN"">Steve Lillywhite</a>, who produced the band\'s first three studio albums. ~ Stephen Thomas Erlewine, Rovi\x1a\x7f\n\x1e\n\x14K\xe0v\xf7@ll\xe6C\x0b\xcb\'\xdeM\x90\x1c\xba\x04\xf3\x0b\x10\x00\x18\x90\x03 Boys\x18\x8e\x01""\xcc\x01\n\x02US\x12\x12\n\x10\x1bIV*\xf9\xcaHJ\xa0\x8b\xca\xf2P\xbcpi\x12\x12\n\x10\xbe\xa8bGk\xf5K5\x8f\x04\x03*\xb2(\x9fY\x12\x12\n\x10\xacs$\x03\xff\xccJq\x9f\x13\x17an\xb4~\xb9\x12\x12\n\x10\xb2Y\xad\xbd`\x95N \xbdtx\xd7\xc3.\xe9\xf2:\x14\n\x12\n\x10\x1a\xba\x08\x97\xe8jJ\x99\xa3\x06\xacmk\xd6\x0e&:\x14\n\x12\n\x10\x0c\x7f\x1d\xedd\xf0NO\xbauo\x19\x05\x0eK\x86:\x14\n\x12\n\x10\xb5\xa0o\x1c\xd0^I$\x94\xd0\x19\x10\xc4\x00\xc5;B\x14\n\x12\n\x10\x9f\x85\x81\x85=pG\xc9\x85\xfd\xc8N\x88+\xec2B\x14\n\x12\n\x10w\xc79\x87\xe2\xe2H\x0e\x8d\x98\xf2#Pq\x13\xd9B\x14\n\x12\n\x10\x8e\xa9\xdd\x90^\xcfMH\xb9\x95\xf8\\\x02IS\x8eB\x14\n\x12\n\x10\xbaE\xfb\xbc\xae`A`\xb7\x82\xc6\xd7\xe1,\x17\x1bB\x14\n\x12\n\x10\xc9\xa1\xf6\xc8\x96\xb4Fj\xb3\xa7\xa8\xc5\xe4\xe3\xd6\x01B\x14\n\x12\n\x10\xefM\xa1\x0e\xc1+DJ\x8buF\xe8\xae\xb2[\xe2B\x14\n\x12\n\x10\x88\x08\xf5\xe76\x89M(\xb0t;\t\x1fU\xa4-B\x14\n\x12\n\x10F\x84l\xab\x14\x8cC\xa9\xa3\x16\\\xd1K\\w\x87B\x14\n\x12\n\x10&;8\xc2\x86dE\xb4\x87>\x13 \xb0u\x93\xc2B(\n\x12\n\x10V,\r\xa9E\x05Ey\x87\xdb\xbb\xc7\x0f\xae\xb0\xd1\n\x12\n\x10m\x18x\x7f\xa3\xc5Gj\x87\xe2\xf3\xb0\xea\x94m\x0cB\x14\n\x12\n\x10<S\xe5\xd4\xe0\xcaIL\xae\xc1\xbdJ\xdc\xeaDvB\x14\n\x12\n\x10\xda\xad|m\xafzOG\x82P\xf5<w\x04\xee5B\x14\n\x12\n\x10\xd6\xb28\xd6\xd3\x9eC`\xbb\xda\xba!\xcew\xc3\x99B\x14\n\x12\n\x10\x1e7\xc7\x9b\xda\xa3O0\x8b\xd1\xec\x80\xe6)\x87\xddB\x14\n\x12\n\x10\xe5p\x02\xd9\xe5\x8fH[\xaetD\xe3\x8f\xc75;B\x14\n\x12\n\x10}M\x99\xffO\xdfG\\\xa43\xc9>\xaf6\xff\xbdB\x14\n\x12\n\x10xW\x9b&\xd4U@\xb2\x83\xe0A\x16\x81\xe1\x90\x84J\x10alternative rockJ\x12east coast hip hopJ\x07hip hopJ\x12old school hip hopJ\x03rapb\xe7b\n\x92RAs the first white rap group of any importance, the Beastie Boys received the scorn of critics and strident hip-hop musicians, both of whom accused them of cultural pirating, especially since they began as a hardcore punk group in 1981. But the Beasties weren\'t pirating -- instead, they treated rap as part of a post-punk musical underground, where the D.I.Y. aesthetics of hip-hop and punk weren\'t that far apart. Of course, the exaggerated b-boy and frat-boy parodies of their unexpected hit debut album, Licensed to Ill, didn\'t help their cause. For much of the mid-\'80s, the Beastie Boys were considered macho clowns, and while they dismissed that theory with the ambitious, <a href=""spotify:artist:4SpGhmdFn74C0Q7D2BhUVG"">Dust Brothers</a>-produced second album, Paul\'s Boutique, it was ignored by both the public and the press at the time. In retrospect, Paul\'s Boutique was one of the first albums to predict the genre-bending, self-referential pop kaleidoscope of \'90s pop. The Beasties refined their eclectic approach with 1992\'s Check Your Head, where they played their own instruments. Check Your Head brought the Beasties back to the top of the charts, and within a few years, they were considered one of the most influential and ambitious groups of the \'90s, cultivating a musical community not only through their music, but with their record label, <a href=""spotify:search:label%3A%22Grand+Royal%22"">Grand Royal</a>, and their magazine of the same name.\r\n\nIt was a remarkable turn of events for a group whose members demonstrated no significant musical talent on their first records. All three members of the Beastie Boys -- Mike D (b. Mike Diamond, November 20, 1966), MCA (b. Adam Yauch, August 5, 1965; d. May 4, 2012), and Ad-Rock (born Adam Horovitz, October 31, 1967) -- came from wealthy middle-class Jewish families in New York and had become involved in the city\'s punk underground when they were teenagers in the early \'80s. Diamond and Yauch formed the Beastie Boys with drummer Kate Schellenbach and guitarist John Berry in 1981, and the group began playing underground clubs around New York. The following year, the Beasties released the 7"" EP Pollywog Stew on the indie label <a href=""spotify:search:label%3A%22Rat+Cage%22"">Rat Cage</a> to little attention. That same year, the band met Horovitz, who had formed the hardcore group the Young and the Useless. By early 1983, Schellenbach and Berry had left the group -- they would later join <a href=""spotify:artist:1EcRE2Nnqg2spdn2otakhg"">Luscious Jackson</a> and Thwig, respectively -- and Horovitz had joined the Beasties. The revamped group released the rap record ""Cookie Puss"" as a 12"" single later in 1983. Based on a prank phone call the group made to Carvel Ice Cream, the single became an underground hit in New York. By early 1984, however, they had abandoned punk and turned their attention to rap.\r\n\nIn 1984, the Beasties joined forces with producer <a href=""spotify:artist:1EpmQFTiJbcxzwbLpuUL8L"">Rick Rubin</a>, a heavy metal and hip-hop fan who had recently founded <a href=""spotify:search:label%3A%22Def+Jam+Records%22"">Def Jam Records</a> with fellow New York University student <a href=""spotify:artist:7HXSDsfCgKWhoeWD31IdWw"">Russell Simmons</a>. <a href=""spotify:search:label%3A%22Def+Jam%22"">Def Jam</a> officially signed the Beastie Boys in 1985, and that year they had a hit single from the soundtrack to Krush Groove with ""She\'s on It,"" a rap track that sampled <a href=""spotify:artist:711MCceyCBcFnzjGY4Q7Un"">AC/DC</a>\'s ""Back in Black"" and suggested the approach of the group\'s forthcoming debut album. The Beasties received their first significant national exposure later in 1985, when they opened for <a href=""spotify:artist:6tbjWDEIzxoDsBA1FuhfPW"">Madonna</a> on her Virgin tour. The Beasties taunted the audience with profanity and were generally poorly received. One other major tour, as the openers for <a href=""spotify:artist:3CQIn7N5CuRDP8wEI7FiDA"">Run-D.M.C.</a>\'s ill-fated Raisin\' Hell trek, followed before Licensed to Ill was released late in 1986. An amalgam of street beats, metal riffs, b-boy jokes, and satire, Licensed to Ill was interpreted as a mindless, obnoxious party record by many critics and conservative action groups. That didn\'t stop the album from becoming the fastest-selling debut in <a href=""spotify:search:label%3A%22Columbia+Records%22"">Columbia Records</a>\' history, however, as it sold over 750,000 copies in its first six weeks. \r\n\nMuch of the album\'s success was due to ""Fight for Your Right (To Party),"" which became a massive crossover single. In fact, Licensed to Ill became the biggest-selling rap album of the \'80s, which generated much criticism from certain hip-hop fans who believed that the Beasties were merely cultural pirates. On the other side of the coin, the group was being attacked from various factions on both the left and the right, who claimed the Beasties\' lyrics were violent and sexist and that their concerts -- which featured female audience members dancing in go-go cages and a giant inflatable penis, similar to what <a href=""spotify:artist:22bE4uQ6baNwSHPVcDxLCe"">the Stones</a> used in their mid-\'70s concerts -- caused even more outrage. Throughout their 1987 tour, they were plagued with arrests and lawsuits, and were accused of inciting crime.\r\n\nWhile much of the Beasties\' exaggeratedly obnoxious behavior started out as a joke, it became a self-parody by the end of 1987, so it wasn\'t a surprise that the group decided to revamp its sound and image during the next two years. During 1988, the Beasties became involved in a bitter lawsuit with <a href=""spotify:search:label%3A%22Def+Jam%22"">Def Jam</a> and <a href=""spotify:artist:1EpmQFTiJbcxzwbLpuUL8L"">Rick Rubin</a>, who claimed he was responsible for their success and threatened to release outtakes as their second album. The Beasties finally broke away by the end of the year and relocated to California, where they signed with <a href=""spotify:search:label%3A%22Capitol+Records%22"">Capitol Records</a>. While in California, they met the production team <a href=""spotify:artist:4SpGhmdFn74C0Q7D2BhUVG"">the Dust Brothers</a>, and they convinced the duo to use their prospective debut album as the basis for the Beasties\' second album, Paul\'s Boutique. Densely layered with interweaving samples and pop culture references, the retro-funk-psychedelia of Paul\'s Boutique was entirely different than Licensed to Ill, and many observers weren\'t quite sure what to make of it. Several publications gave it rave reviews, but when it failed to produce a single bigger than the number 36 ""Hey Ladies,"" it was quickly forgotten about. \r\n\nDespite its poor commercial performance, Paul\'s Boutique gained a cult following, and its cut-and-paste sample techniques would later be hailed as visionary, especially after <a href=""spotify:artist:4SpGhmdFn74C0Q7D2BhUVG"">the Dust Brothers</a> altered the approach for <a href=""spotify:artist:3vbKDsSS70ZX9D2OcvbZmS"">Beck</a>\'s acclaimed 1996 album, Odelay. Still, the record was declared a disaster in the early \'90s, but that didn\'t prevent the Beasties from building their own studio and founding their own record label, <a href=""spotify:search:label%3A%22Grand+Royal%22"">Grand Royal</a>, for their next record, Check Your Head. Alternating between old-school hip-hop, raw amateurish funk, and hardcore punk, Check Your Head was less accomplished than Paul\'s Boutique, but equally diverse. Furthermore, the burgeoning cult around the Beasties made the album a surprise Top Ten hit upon its spring 1992 release. ""Jimmy James,"" ""Pass the Mic,"" and ""So Whatcha Want"" were bigger hits on college and alternative rock radio than they were on rap radio, and the group suddenly became hip again. \r\n\nEarly in 1994, they collected their early punk recordings on the compilation Some Old Bullshit, which was followed in June by their fourth album, Ill Communication. Essentially an extension of Check Your Head, the record debuted at number one upon its release, and the singles ""Sabotage"" and ""Sure Shot"" helped send it to double-platinum status. During the summer of 1994, they co-headlined the fourth Lollapalooza festival with <a href=""spotify:artist:40Yq4vzPs9VNUrIBG5Jr2i"">the Smashing Pumpkins</a>. That same year, <a href=""spotify:search:label%3A%22Grand+Royal%22"">Grand Royal</a> became a full-fledged record label as it released <a href=""spotify:artist:1EcRE2Nnqg2spdn2otakhg"">Luscious Jackson</a>\'s acclaimed debut album, Natural Ingredients. The Beasties\' <a href=""spotify:search:label%3A%22Grand+Royal%22"">Grand Royal</a> magazine was also launched that year.\r\n\nOver the next few years, the Beasties remained quiet as they concentrated on political causes and the machinations of their record label. In 1996, they released the hardcore EP Aglio e Olio and the instrumental soul-jazz and funk collection The In Sound from Way Out! Also that year, Adam Yauch organized a two-day festival to raise awareness about the plight of Tibet, and the festival went on to become an annual event. The Beastie Boys\' long-awaited fifth LP, Hello Nasty, finally appeared during the summer of 1998 and became their third chart-topping album. A longer wait preceded release of their next record, To the 5 Boroughs, which appeared in mid-2004. In 2005, <a href=""spotify:search:label%3A%22Capitol%22"">Capitol</a> issued Solid Gold Hits, a 15-track survey of the Beasties\' lengthy career. One year later, the band released a concert film titled Awesome: I Fuckin\' Shot That!, which had been pieced together from footage shot by 50 DV and Hi-8 cameras that had been distributed to fans. The DVD version appeared in July of that year. \r\n\nAn instrumental album, The Mix-Up, continued the band\'s prolific activity in 2007 and garnered a Grammy Award the following year. The Beastie Boys returned to rap with Hot Sauce Committee, Pt. 1, parts of which were previewed during the band\'s performance at the 2009 Bonnaroo festival, but the album ended up unreleased in the wake of Yauch\'s announcement that he had cancer. He underwent successful surgery and radiation treatment, and the band announced late in 2010 that Hot Sauce Committee, Pt. 2 (including virtually all the material intended for the first volume) would be released in 2011. They made good on their promise; the album appeared in May, and was positively received both critically and commercially. One year later, however, in May of 2012, Yauch finally succumbed to his cancer. ~ Stephen Thomas Erlewine, T\n\x1e\n\x14\xdfAE\xad4\xf0\xc9\x94\x8e\xf7\xa0p\xfb\xccFZ\xc1\xb9}\xba\x10\x02\x18\x80\n \xd0\x06\n\x1e\n\x14\xc8\x1dE\xcd\r\x01;l""\x96\xca\x90t\xa78c\x00&\x1d\x18\x10\x03\x18\xd0\x0f
